[[File:Paulina Rubio @ Asics Music Festival 06.jpg|thumb|alt=Paulina Rubio, a young, blonde woman, sings into a microphone onstage|[[Paulina Rubio]] takes the role of a "seductive, sexy, young woman who wants a macho-man at heart" in her music.]]
[[File:Gloria Trevi Mexican pop.jpg|thumb|alt=Gloria Trevi, a young woman with short hair, singing into a wireless microphone onstage|[[Gloria Trevi]] (pictured) and [[Alejandra Guzmán]] were the first women in the [[Top Latin Albums]] chart's 24-year history to have a number-one collaborative album in 2017.]]
[[File:Julieta Venegas primer plano.jpg|thumb|alt=Julieta Venegas, a young woman with dark hair, singing onstage|Although [[Julieta Venegas]] does not call herself a [[feminist]], she said that her music reflects a woman's point of view.]]
Women have made significant contributions to [[Latin music (genre)|Latin music]], a genre which predates Italian explorer [[Christopher Columbus]]' arrival in Latin America in 1492 and the [[Spanish colonization of the Americas]]. The earliest musicians were [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]], hundreds of [[ethnic group]]s across the continent, whose lyrics "reflect conflict, beauty, pain, and loss that mark all [[human experience]]." Indigenous communities reserved [[women in music|music for women]], who were given equal opportunities with men to teach, perform, sing, and dance. [[Ethnomusicologist]]s have measured ceramic, animal-bone, and cane [[flute]]s from the [[Inca Empire]] which indicate a preference for women with a high [[vocal range]]. Women had equal [[social status]], were trained, and received the same opportunities in music as men in indigenous communities until the arrival of Columbus in the late 15th century. European settlers brought patriarchal, [[machismo]] ideologies to the continent, replacing the idea of equality between men and women. They equated [[Native American music|native music]] with "savagery" and European music with "civilization". Female musicians tended to be darker-skinned as a result of the [[slave trade]] (which increased the population of [[African slaves]]), and contemporary society denigrated music as a profession. Latin music became Africanized, with [[syncopated]] [[rhythm (music)|rhythms]] and [[call-and-response]]; European settlement introduced [[harmony]] and the Spanish [[décima]] song form.

Since the [[history of sound recording|pre-recording era of music]], Latin music was male-dominated, and there are relatively few examples of female [[songwriter]]s, [[music producer]]s, [[record executive]]s, and [[music promoter|promoters]]. Women lacked access to musical training; music programs were nonexistent, and cultural norms discouraged female participation. Latin music had a primarily male presence; men discriminated against women, limiting them to singing or dancing and discouraging them from becoming [[instrumentalist]]s, writers, [[List of women composers|composers]], [[music arranger|arrangers]], and executives. Women artists in the sub-genres of Latin music, such as [[Selena]], [[Jenni Rivera]], [[Jennifer Lopez]], [[Ivy Queen]], [[Julieta Venegas]], and [[Ely Guerra]]. have been credited with enhancing the genres' female presence; they have broken through barriers, reshaping Latin music and public perceptions of [[female sexuality]], gender, and [[femininity]]. Women in [[salsa music]] are significantly underrepresented in the industry as very few women, with the exception of [[Celia Cruz]], have been associated with the emergence of the genre; for example, in the British documentary ''Salsa: Latin Pop Music in the Cites'' (1985), Cruz is one of the only female singers who is mentioned.

Women Latin singers have a significant demographic imbalance on [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] [[music charts]] compared with their male counterparts. As radio formats explore genres popularized and led by men, such as [[reggaeton]] and [[regional Mexican music]], women on the ''Billboard'' Latin music charts are periodically absent. The last female singer with a number-one single was [[Sofia Reyes]], whose collaborative "[[Solo Yo]]" ended a five-year drought on the [[Latin Pop Songs]] chart in 2016. A year earlier, on the 50-position [[Hot Latin Songs]] chart, 22 weeks passed without a song by a women. Reyes has expressed concern about the disparity between male and female performances at Latin music award shows, noting that 90 percent of the performers are male. Other female singers, such as [[Chiquis Rivera]], have attributed the decline in visibility of women in Latin music to  [[sexist]] radio programmers. Latin music executive Alexandra Lioutikoff believes that the decline is due to a lack of female collaboration. Latin music remains male-dominated, and the [[music industry]] has "prejudiced practice" limiting female recording artists.

== Characteristics ==
Latin American music is varied; it includes thirty countries, influenced by [[European music|European]], [[African American music|African]], and [[Native American music|Amerindian]] cultures.{{sfn|Roberts|1999|p=3}} Latin music uses two European languages: [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], though modern-day widely distinguishes the genre as primarily sung or recorded in Spanish and to a lesser extent [[French language|French]] and [[Italian language|Italian]].{{sfn|Roberts|1999|p=3}} Although heterogeneous, Latin music commonly includes the Spanish [[décima]] song form, African [[syncopation|syncopated]] [[rhythm (music)|rhythms]] and [[call-and-response]], and European [[harmony (music)|harmony]].{{sfn|Miller|2008|p=254}}

== History ==
=== Pre-Columbian Latin America ===
[[File:Peru Tembladera Figure flute player DMA 1971-19.jpg|thumb|alt=Squat, reddish ceramic figurine of a person holding a flute|Pre-Columbian ceramic figurine of a Peruvian flute player]]
Pre-modern Latin music refers to music made by [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]],{{sfn|Kuss|2004|p=1}} hundreds of [[ethnic group]]s across the continent.{{sfn|Navarro|Sánchez|Ali|1999|p=5}} The first inhabitants of Latin America settled 30,000 years before the arrival of Italian explorer [[Christopher Columbus]] at the peak of native cultural diversification into simple and complex societies.{{sfn|Preston|2014|p=11}} These societies included sedentary agricultural tribes and [[hunter gatherers]],{{sfn|Preston|2014|p=11}} who sang [[prayer]]s to a deity asking for prosperity{{sfn|Kuss|2004|p=1}} with lyrics of "conflict, beauty, pain, and loss that mark all human experience" and music reflecting their understanding of the universe.{{sfn|Kuss|2004|p=5}} They had "intricate ways of explaining the relationships between the sound, social organization, time, and the sacred",{{sfn|Kuss|2004|p=5}} and their rituals included dramatized performances of mythology vocalizing their view of [[creationism|creation]].{{sfn|Kuss|2004|p=8}} The creation myth of the [[Keres people]] of [[Laguna Pueblo]] (present west-central [[New Mexico]]) describes "the unformed cosmos as the domain of [[Tse che nako]] (Thought Woman or Spider Woman) who [[chant]]s life into two sacred bundles that become the sisters [[Keres (mythology)|Uretsete and Naosete]] (She Who Matters and She Who Remembers)."{{sfn|Kuss|2004|p=8}}

Indigenous communities predating Columbus' arrival reserved [[women in music|music for women]], although men were equally involved in dance.{{sfn|Kuss|2004|p=170}} During the [[Inca Empire]] in the mid-14th century, women from royal families and selected ''acallas'' (chosen ones) were taught science, art, poetry, and music from "wise elders".{{sfn|Pendle|2001|p=442}} The "chosen ones" were selected for their beauty and "quality of their voices."{{sfn|Pendle|2001|p=442}} There were six houses, one of which was called the ''taquiaclla'' (''taqui'' means "song"),<!-- In what language? --> which housed girls aged nine to fifteen with "gifted" singing voices.{{sfn|Pendle|2001|p=442}} The [[Andean civilizations|Andeans]] preferred young women with a high [[vocal range]].{{sfn|Pendle|2001|p=442}} Although no scripts or musical notation survive, archaeologists have uncovered a variety of ceramic, animal bone, and cane [[flute]]s.{{sfn|Pendle|2001|p=442}} [[Ethnomusicologist]]s who have measured the flutes have found their [[pitch (music)|pitch]] compatible with a high vocal range.{{sfn|Pendle|2001|p=442}} Women in these communities were well-treated,{{sfn|Tompkins|Foster|2001|p=34}} with equal opportunities to teach, perform, sing, and dance (as soloists, with other women, or in pairs with men).{{sfn|Kuss|2004|p=139}} Female singers had a social status equal to men, receiving musical training and opportunities with their male counterparts.{{sfn|Sturman|2015}}

=== {{anchor|Arrival of European settlers}}European arrival ===
[[File:Columbus landing on Hispaniola adj.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Europeans and natives meeting, with ships and a missionary cross in the background|Christopher Columbus' arrival in the Americas and Spanish colonization brought patriarchy and machismo to Latin music.]]
Columbus' arrival in 1492 and the [[Spanish colonization of the Americas]] brought [[patriarchy]] and [[machismo]] to the continent, overriding sexual equality.{{sfn|Tompkins|Foster|2001|p=34}} Early [[Music of Spain|Spanish music]] described women as "property and mistrusted [by men]."{{sfn|Sturman|2015}} In a song, "Delgadina", women are servants who must please their men "no matter the cost."{{sfn|Sturman|2015}} According to author Janet Sturman, the Iberian idea of machismo (in which a strong man is superior to others, including women) was held by the [[conquistadors]].{{sfn|Sturman|2015}} Europeans who settled in the [[New World]] associated native music with "savagery" and European music with "civilization".{{sfn|Berglund|Johnson|Lee|2016|p=17}} During the [[slave trade]], musicians in Latin America primarily had a dark complexion.{{sfn|Baker|Knighton|2011|p=154}} This was due to an increased population of African slaves and contemporary society's view of music as a profession.{{sfn|Baker|Knighton|2011|p=154}} Most slaves arriving in Brazil were "bi-musical",<!-- "Bi-musical" needs explanation. --> and introduced their music to [[Music of Brazil|the country]].{{sfn|Baker|Knighton|2011|p=154}} Rural [[Quechua language|Quechua]]-speaking [[Bolivia]]n farmers sang about European resistance in songs with Native American and European influences.{{sfn|Pendle|2001|p=439}} [[Dark skin|Black]] Bolivians sang songs with lyrics reflecting a European influence, performed as Africanized European music.{{sfn|Pendle|2001|p=439}}

In colonial Latin America, [[nun]]s wrote, directed, and performed music.{{sfn|Socolow|2000|p=102}} They played a variety of instruments, including the [[clavichord]], [[harp]], [[flageolet]], and flute.{{sfn|Socolow|2000|p=102}} The nuns played in front of spectators, choirs, and high-ranking government officials.{{sfn|Socolow|2000|p=102}} Musically-adept, underprivileged women were allowed to perform during the nuns' [[Christmas]] recital.{{sfn|Socolow|2000|p=102}} Performances were often "feminine acts", such as sewing, embroidery, bakery, and selling "special confections."{{sfn|Socolow|2000|p=102}} For two hundred years in Latin America, the "elite woman" was educated in the arts; "the rest" were consigned to cooking, sewing, spinning, weaving, embroidery, and music.{{sfn|Socolow|2000|p=167}} In 17th- and 18th-century [[Mexico City]], music was often heard by visitors.{{sfn|Baker|Knighton|2011|p=50}} The music emanated from cathedral choirs, indigenous dancers, or black musicians organized in the city.{{sfn|Baker|Knighton|2011|p=50}} During the 17th century, Europeans and their descendants wrote and performed music at cathedrals in Mexico's cities which was repeated in song by [[black people|blacks]], [[mulatto]]s, indigenous Mexicans, [[Asian people|Asians]], and ethnicities.{{sfn|Baker|Knighton|2011|p=49}} In 1690, Mexican author [[Sor Juana Inés de la Cruz]] wrote secular and religious poetry, plays, philosophy, and theology.{{sfn|Socolow|2000|p=103}} She often discussed topics ranging from mathematics to music with visitors, had no interest in marriage and wanted to pursue "a life of the mind."{{sfn|Socolow|2000|p=103}} Although her views were suppressed, de la Cruz defended [[women's rights]] in education.{{sfn|Socolow|2000|p=103}}

At a 1691 celebration, European traveler Juan de Galde described his participation in dancing and singing and placing a [[scapular]] on two young women in Mexico.{{sfn|Baker|Knighton|2011|p=50}} A Mexican singer named Reina performed for six hours, which made "the event more enjoyable".{{sfn|Baker|Knighton|2011|pp=50-51}} The "wild" celebration banned [[Jamaicans]] from entry.{{sfn|Baker|Knighton|2011|p=51}} In 1697, Neapolitan chronicler Gemelli Carreri wrote during his trip off the coast of the [[Dominican Republic]] that he saw a canoe of musicians trying to outdo each other in singing and drawing attention to their "perfection".{{sfn|Baker|Knighton|2011|p=50}} In 1799 [[Buenos Aires]], privileged women were encouraged to educate themselves in the arts.{{sfn|Socolow|2000|p=170}} The government required that women be taught to read and write, in addition to physical education and music.{{sfn|Socolow|2000|p=170}}

=== {{anchor|Pre-recorded era of Latin music}}Before recordings ===
Since the arrival of European settlers, Latin music has been male-dominated.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=267}} Musical training was nonexistent for women.{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=137}} Male predominance in the genre left "power imbalances that acted as barriers to women's participation in Latin music."{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=267}} Despite this barrier, women have become successful.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=267}} Under the authority of men, they were limited to roles as [[vocalist]]s or dancers rather than [[instrumentalists]], writers, composers, [[music arranger|arrangers]], and executives.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=267}} According to musicologist [[Ilan Stavans]], female roles were related to traditional norms; "decent women" cared for their children and remained at home, cleaning and cooking.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=267}} Women's dance routines were a growing concern among female fans and performers.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=267}} Female dancers, more closely scrutinized than males, were expected to follow "normative gender expectations" and exhibit "appropriate behavior".{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=268}} Although male dancers typically performed suggestively, women who danced similarly were accused of being "loose" or "slack".{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=268}}

== Genres ==
=== Tropical music ===
[[File:Celia Cruz 1.jpg|thumb|alt=Black-and-white photo of Celia Cruz onstage in a fluffy gown|[[Celia Cruz]], who broke barriers against women in [[salsa music]], was instrumental in popularizing the genre.]]
According to author Lise Waxer, Cuban [[trova]] singer [[María Teresa Vera]] is the "great-grandmother of all Latin women singers".{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=147}} "Arroz Con Leche" ("Rice Pudding"), which advises the listener to find a spouse who will take care of them, was criticized by [[feminist]] groups.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=37}} [[Bolero]] lyrics have a central theme of women as the object of male desire, [[unrequited love]], and abandonment, portraying women as "physical absence and emotional distance, as ungrateful beings" unequipped to love a man.{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=137}} Cuban singer [[La Lupe]] "pushed the boundaries" of bolero music, and was called the queen of [[Latin soul]] music.{{sfn|Poey|2014}} She toured the U.S. with bandleader [[Tito Puente]], and was one of the most popular Latin performers of the 1960s.{{sfn|Pareles|1992}} In her youth she dominated local singing competitions, which inspired her to pursue a career in music despite her parents' desire for her to become a teacher.{{sfn|Pareles|1992}} After divorcing her first husband, La Lupe began a solo career and performed in [[Havana]] nightclubs.{{sfn|Pareles|1992}} Her popularity grew, and she owned and operated a nightclub in Cuba which was seized by the [[Cuba under Fidel Castro|Castro government]].{{sfn|Pareles|1992}} La Lupe emigrated to the United States, settled in New York in 1962 and began touring the country with other bolero and salsa performers.{{sfn|Pareles|1992}} She released several salsa albums with "devotional lyrics."{{sfn|Pareles|1992}} Her concert requests began diminishing at the turn of the 1970s as her savings drained because of her second husband's failing health.{{sfn|Pareles|1992}} She ended her professional career in a wheelchair at a final, 1985 concert with Puente to help pay her medical expenses.{{sfn|Pareles|1992}} La Lupe, who devoted her remaining years to [[Christian music]] in [[the Bronx]], died of [[cardiac arrest]] in February 1992.{{sfn|Pareles|1992}} Cuban singers [[Rita Montaner]] and [[Celeste Mendoza]] were involved in the "appropriation and rearticulation of [[rhumba|rumba]]", a genre popular before salsa.{{sfn|Poey|2014}}

As [[salsa music]] grew in popularity, [[Celia Cruz]] emerged during the 1950s and was known as the queen of the genre.{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=136}} Although Cruz was instrumental in popularizing and developing male-dominated salsa,{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=137}} few other women are associated with it.{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=137}} She was the only female singer featured in the British documentary, ''Salsa: Latin Pop Music in the Cities'' (1985), which noted the absence of women in the industry.{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=137}} According to the documentary, women were "not trained in popular music and that women dared not improvise—''sonear'' (closeness)—on stage".{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=137}} Cruz crossed boundaries set by public expectations for music performed at nightclubs, but she was the exception who proved the rule.{{sfn|Poey|2014}} Opportunities for all-female salsa bands were nonexistent; gender discrimination flourished in the market, and women were seen as "less competent than their male counterparts."{{sfn|Poey|2014}} In 1977 Cruz recorded "Usted Abusó", which gave a voice to [[violence against women|battered women]].{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=268}} The 1980s saw the emergence of [[salsa romántica]], which was "deemed as homogenized, depoliticized, and ultimately, feminized."{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=137}}

[[File:Gloriaestefan ahoy.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Gloria Estefan onstage, singing and holding flowers|In 1993, [[Gloria Estefan]] was the first musician to debut an album atop the ''Billboard'' [[Top Latin Albums]] chart.]]
During the 1990s women began playing a larger role in salsa music,{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=14}} increasing the genre's popularity,{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=136}} and female salsa singers broke "the sexist boundaries of the [Latin] music industry".{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=147}} Although women singers were becoming more popular, images of men were emphasized to the public more than those of women.{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=14}} [[La India]], Corinne, [[Brenda K. Starr]], [[Lissette Melendez]], and Yolanda la Duke were instrumental in refining salsa in that decade, although all were managed by men.{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=136}} Their new salsa sound was influenced by African American music ([[hip hop music|hip-hop]], [[contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[gospel music|gospel]], [[jazz music|jazz]], and [[soul music|soul]]), which revolutionized traditional 1970s salsa.{{sfn|Waxer|2002|p=136}} According to author Lise Waxer, a "careful and attentive listening" of their recordings indicated the "female authority and influence—a female genealogy—of salsa music."{{sfn|Waxer|2002|pp=136, 147}} Salsa's leading female singer was [[La India]],{{sfn|Candelaria|2004|p=412}} who developed salsa romantica music during the 1990s and whose lyrics "turn the tables" on the male salsa narrative of women as objects of desire, "cruel and evil or idealized and unattainable."{{sfn|Poey|2014}} In her most-popular song, "[[Ese Hombre (Rocío Jurado song)|Ese Hombre]]" (originally recorded by [[Rocío Jurado]]), La India contradicts male stereotypes.{{sfn|Poey|2014}} The song's lyrics describe a man who is "a fool/stupid and conceited/selfish and capricious", reversing male "discursive terrorism" toward their female partners.{{sfn|Poey|2014}} La India has been compared to Celia Cruz as leaders in their respective eras,{{sfn|Candelaria|2004|p=413}} and to La Lupe in musical style: "nasal style of singing, growls, and screams that evoke an androgynous style rather than a soft melodious tone."{{sfn|Poey|2014}}

In her Spanish-language debut, [[Gloria Estefan]] released ''[[Mi Tierra]]'' (1993). It was a commercial success, debuting atop the new US [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] [[Top Latin Albums]] chart. Estefan has been described by her [[Latin pop]] contemporaries as performing [[pop ballad]]s and [[soft rock]].{{sfn|Aparicio|2010|p=113}} She has also ventured into salsa and [[merengue music]], using salsa in her English-language compositions; "[[Conga (song)|Conga]]" brought her to European clubs.{{sfn|Broughton|Ellingham|Trillo|1999|p=499}} The rural Cuban genre [[guajira (music)|guajira]] offered a musical identity to [[Afro-Cuban]]s;{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=305}} [[Albita Rodriguez]] became popular, and was named one of the top 100 personalities of the 20th century by ''[[Newsweek (magazine)|Newsweek]]'' magazine.{{sfn|Novas|2007|p=323}} Most of her repertoire are love songs with "openly erotic lyrics" with hetero- and homosexual themes.{{sfn|Aparicio|2010|p=243}}

The duo of [[Monchy y Alexandra]] "established [[bachata (music)|bachata]] as a [[easy listening|'nice']] music that could be listened to in the home by women and children."{{sfn|Hernandez|2010|p=91}} Women "embraced [the] clean-up"; the romantic bachata style, with emotive lyrics, expressed longing for a lost lover.{{sfn|Hernandez|2010|p=91}} In 1950s bachata music, women were accused of "treachery or promiscuity or, in more humorous moments, referring to [[women sexuality|their sexuality]] and sexual organs with thinly veiled double entendres."{{sfn|Hernandez|2010|p=89}} The lyrics were rooted in an era where [[women in the workplace]] became more common, displacing men as [[breadwinner]]s.{{sfn|Hernandez|2010|p=89}}

In 19th-century merengue music, a man "won the love of woman" by dancing.{{sfn|Austerlitz|1997|p=34}} Modern merengue (a [[club music|party]] genre) lyrics explored the "vicissitudes of urban life [and] employed skillful wordplay and humorous double entendres about women and sex."{{sfn|Hernandez|2010|p=88}} Because of the genre's "air of male-dominated sexuality", [[People of the Dominican Republic|Dominican]] men believed that making merengue music is "no fitting occupation for women."{{sfn|Austerlitz|1997|p=116}} According to [[Santo Domingo|Santo Domingans]], listening to merengue music "is only for men" and a woman who enjoys the music is considered "a crazy girl [and] a bad girl."{{sfn|Austerlitz|1997|p=116}} During the 1970s, attitudes toward women and merengue music changed with the changing roles of women in Dominican society.{{sfn|Austerlitz|1997|p=116}} All-female merengue bands emerged in the 1980s, beginning with [[Las Chicas Del Can]] in 1984.{{sfn|Austerlitz|1997|p=116}} Participation in merengue increased in 1990, with women playing [[percussion]] and [[brass]] instruments formerly considered too difficult for women.{{sfn|Austerlitz|1997|p=116}}

Female merengue bands were often formed by successful male merengue musicians, who "often referred to them as the property of the [male musicians who formed them]."{{sfn|Austerlitz|1997|p=117}} The mainly-female merengue band [[Milly y los Vecinos|Milly, Jocelyn y Los Vecinos]] formed after Las Chicas del Can.{{sfn|Austerlitz|1997|p=117}} The group became popular, despite not setting out to challenge existing gender roles.{{sfn|Austerlitz|1997|p=117}} Feminists have noted the "limited values" in merengue recordings by women, since most of their songs are written by men who "do not resolutely challenge patriarchal attitudes."{{sfn|Austerlitz|1997|p=118}} [[Olga Tañón]] was the most successful female merengue artist in the 1990s,{{sfn|Hernandez|2010|p=88}} and has been called the queen of merengue music.{{sfn|Steingress|2002|p=13}} Tañón has been credited with popularizing merengue in [[Music of Puerto Rico|Puerto Rico]], a salsa-dominated market.{{sfn|Morales|2003|p=248}} Her 1994 album, ''Siente el Amor'', outsold her previous recordings: ''[[Mujer de Fuego]]'' (1993) and her platinum-certified debut studio album, ''[[Sola]]'' (1992).{{sfn|Morales|2003|p=248}}

=== Regional Mexican music ===
[[File:Selena Memorial02.jpg|thumb|alt=Memorial to Selena, featuring a statue of her standing with one knee bent|[[Selena]] (her [[Mirador de la Flor|memorial]] is pictured) was the first Hispanic artist to debut atop the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart.]]
Since the [[history of radio|beginning of radio]] women have been accepted as [[mariachi]] singers, often performing duets with men.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=467}} The Mexican quintet Las Coronelas, formed by María Carlota Noriega during the 1940s, was the first mariachi [[all-female band]].{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=467}} The first all-female [[ranchera]] band, Las Generales (formed by Elena Muñoz), consisted of wives and mothers of male professional mariachi musicians.{{sfn|Greathouse|2009|p=112}} The group was criticized by the public for playing in ''[[cantina]]s'' ([[bar]]s),{{sfn|Greathouse|2009|p=112}} and their partners destroyed their instruments.{{sfn|Greathouse|2009|p=112}} Other all-female bands tried unsuccessfully to be pioneers. Four of the six-member Mariachi Estrella de Topeka and 110 others were killed in the 1981 [[Hyatt Regency walkway collapse]].{{sfn|Greathouse|2009|p=112}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www2.ljworld.com/news/2010/feb/20/mariachi-divina-new-film-celebrates-legacy-kansas-/|author=Gavon Laessig|date=February 20, 2010|title=Mariachi Divina: New film celebrates legacy of Kansas mariachi legends, Mariachi Estrella de Topeka|newspaper=[[Lawrence Journal-World]]|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref> Rebecca Gonzales, who later joined the [[Los Angeles]] Uclatlan band, was the first female mariachi [[violinist]].{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=467}} According to Gonzales, the other members of Uclatlan found it "bizarre" that a woman was playing with them and it took the group about a month to accept her.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|pp=467-468}} Gonzales was the first female mariachi musician to break through professionally.{{sfn|Greathouse|2009|p=112}} A role model for female mariachi hopefuls, she was inducted into the Mariachi Hall of Fame in [[Tucson, Arizona]] in 2004.{{sfn|Greathouse|2009|p=115}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tucsonmariachi.org/hall-of-fame/|title=Mariachi Hall of Fame|website=Tucson International Mariachi Conference|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref> Eva Ybarra mastered the [[accordion]] at a young age and began performing with her parents during the 1940s.{{sfn|Anon.|n.d. (b)}} The 1962 film ''El Mariachi Canta'' pokes fun at the rarity of female mariachi singers, with men [[cross-dressing]] as women.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=467}}

[[Linda Ronstadt]] debuted on the Latin-music scene with ''[[Canciones de Mi Padre]]'' (1987), credited with inspiring a mariachi renaissance in the United States.{{sfn|Greathouse|2009|p=112}} Other moderately-successful mariachi singers are educator and Mariachi Hall of Famer Laura Sobrino, Cindy Reifer, Marisa Orduno, trumpeter [[Cindy Shea]], [[Patricia Martin]], and Judith Kamel.{{sfn|Greathouse|2009|pp=115-116}} In [[corrido]], a [[ballad]] form consisting of four-line verses,{{sfn|Stacy|2002|p=231}} women played supporting roles as mothers, wives "or represented the subject of the protagonist's affections."{{sfn|Sturman|2015}} Female soldiers in the [[Mexican Revolution]] were styled as ''corridistas''.{{sfn|Sturman|2015}} Women were discouraged from playing and singing [[Tejano music]] due to [[Tejano]] patriarchy.{{sfn|San Miguel|2002|p=116}} Only a handful of female Tejano singers, including Chavela Ortiz, [[Lisa Lopez]], Patsy Torres, [[Laura Canales]], and [[Elsa Garcia]], were successful in the genre before it became popular.{{sfn|San Miguel|2002|p=116}} Other female singers who were moderately successful during the Tejano golden age were [[Shelly Lares]], Stefani Montiel, Mary Lee Ochoa, and Stephanie Lynn.{{sfn|San Miguel|2002|pp=116-118}} 
[[File:LindaRonstadtPerforming.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Linda Ronstadt, with short dark hair, singing onstage|[[Linda Ronstadt]] is credited with inspiring the mariachi renaissance in the United States.]]
At the turn of the decade, Tejano music was the fastest-growing music genre in the United States.{{sfn|Anon.|1996|p=10}} The American singer [[Selena]] dominated Tejano music, bringing it [[mainstream]] success.{{sfn|Lomelí|Ikas|2000|p=58}}{{sfn|Stavans|1998|p=5}} During her early career, she was often turned down by music venues because of her age and her fronting of [[Selena y Los Dinos|a Tejano band]].{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=112}} Selena's father, [[Abraham Quintanilla, Jr.]] was told that she would not be successful because she was a woman.{{sfn|Patoski|1996|p=112}} She was the first female Tejano singer to receive gold and platinum certifications,{{sfn|Roterman|1995}}{{sfn|Richmond|1995|p=48}} the first female Tejano singer to receive a [[Grammy Award for Best Mexican/Mexican-American Album|Grammy Award for Best Mexican American Album]],{{sfn|Stacy|2002|p=746}} the first Tejano singer to top the US [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] [[Top Latin Albums]] chart,{{sfn|Lannert|1994 (a)|p=34, 103}} and the first female to outsell male Tejano singers.{{sfn|Patoski|2000}}{{sfn|Acosta|2006}} After Selena's 1995 [[Murder of Selena|murder]], Tejano music waned in popularity.{{sfn|Paredez|2009|p=21}} Selena's popularity increased after her death, and she is the only Tejano singer with constant appearances on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=498}} Her posthumously-released album, ''[[Dreaming of You (Selena album)|Dreaming of You]]'' (1995), was the first recording by a Hispanic singer to debut atop the ''Billboard'' 200 chart.{{sfn|Marrero|2003|p=172}}{{sfn|Burr|2005|p=56}} Selena's music explored love, pain, strength and passion,{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=725}} and ''Billboard'' called her the best-selling Latin artist of the 1990s.{{sfn|Mayfield|1999|p=YE-16-18}} Latin music entered the mainstream market in the late 1990s, believed by music critics to be due to the death of Selena and the emergence of [[Ricky Martin]], [[Christina Aguilera]], [[Jennifer Lopez]] and [[Marc Anthony]],{{sfn|Márquez|2001}}{{sfn|Brill|2010}} with greater commercial success and worldwide recognition than ever before.{{sfn|Rivera-Servera|2012|p=10}}

As Tejano music declined in popularity, [[norteño (music)|norteño]] music was pioneered by [[Lydia Mendoza]] and [[Alicia Villareal]].{{sfn|San Miguel|2002|p=118}} Although [[Ilan Stavans]] found it challenging to describe Mexican singer [[Jenni Rivera]] as a feminist, he found that her recordings sparked debate in the Latino community about women's roles.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=671}} Debuting on the music scene in 1994, Rivera's music "addresses the lives of men and women of humble backgrounds".{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=671}} She was commercially successful as a vocalist in the regional Mexican music scene and its subgenres, [[banda (music)|banda]], [[conjunto]] (small band) and Tejano, before her 2012 death in a plane crash.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=671}} Mexican singer [[Lila Downs]] debuted on the Latin-music scene with her album, ''[[Ofrenda]]'', in 1994.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=290}} Downs, a prolific innovator, popularized Latin [[folk music]] in recordings blending folk instrumentals with [[Oaxaca]] references.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=290}}

[[Ana Bárbara]] is the leading female in [[grupera]], a regional Mexican folk genre,{{sfn|Lannert|2000 (a)|p=LM-38}} and [[Jennifer Peña]] was called "one of Latin music's most promising female singers" by ''Billboard'' magazine.{{sfn|Cobo|2007 (b)|p=36}} The mid-2000s decline of women in regional Mexican music slowed, with greater representation by [[Graciela Beltran]], [[Yolanda Perez]], [[Los Horóscopos de Durango]], [[Diana Reyes]], and Jenni Rivera.{{sfn|Cobo|2007 (b)|p=25}}

=== Urban music ===
[[File:Ivy Queen, 2010.jpg|thumb|alt=Ivy Queen onstage with long, blonde hair|[[Ivy Queen]] confronted negative reaction to women's sexually-suggestive dance moves in [[reggaeton]].]]
As [[hip-hop]] and [[rap music|rap]] became popular in the United States during the 1990s, Latin singers began emulating them.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=333}} Men dominated the Latin urban scene; women were objectified, seen as accessories indicating male status.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=333}} Unlike the hip-hop and rap music scenes, their Latin equivalents did not formulate a female role model; female Latina urban singers failed to attain commercial success.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=333}} During the popularity of [[Latin freestyle]] (also called freestyle music or [[Latin hip-hop]]) in the 1980s, record companies began signing "attractive young women with little musical talent using the same production style for all of them, weakening rather than strengthening the style."{{sfn|Hernandez|2010|p=64}} Many Hispanic freestyle singers tried to downplay their Latino identity after radio programmers discriminated against records by Hispanic performers.{{sfn|Hernandez|2010|p=64}} Lisa Velez changed her name to [[Lisa Lisa and Cult Jam|Lisa Lisa]], and became one of the first commercially successful freestyle musicians.{{sfn|Hernandez|2010|p=64}} Latin hip-hop singer Roja (one half of Rima Roja en Venus) expressed the difficulty of performing (in a male-dominated genre) a song which "insults based on having sex with the opponent's mother, sister, aunt; or calling each other by the names of women's sexual organs. It was bizarre: they were managing to totally objectify women, and at the same time make us invisible."{{sfn|Rigby|2015}} According to Roja, in her early career as a [[rapping|rap]] [[freestyler]] men tried to "shut [her] up".{{sfn|Rigby|2015}} Other female hip-hop singers, such as Argentinian [[MC]] Rebeca Lane and Ecuadorian Audry Funk, concur.{{sfn|Rigby|2015}} Argentinian Actitud María Marta, a hip-hop group formed in prison, has been called a pioneer and has inspired other female hip-hop singers.{{sfn|Rigby|2015}} 

[[Reggaeton]] dancers (to music exemplifying sexual desire) have received a negative public reception of their sexually-suggestive routines,{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=268}} with most public outcry about this type of dance focusing on female morality.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=268}} Reggaeton singer [[Ivy Queen]] addressed concerns in her 2003 single, "[[Quiero Bailar (song)|Yo Quiero Bailar]]", which confronts sexual accessibility; dancing suggestively with a man does not necessarily mean that she wants to sleep with him.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=268}} Recording Reggaeton Women called Ivy Queen "the spokeswoman for females in reggaeton" after her 2005 debut album, and she remains the only woman visible in the genre.{{sfn|Rivera|Marshall|Hernandez|2010|p=239}} Reggaeton has been criticized for the roles women play.{{sfn|Rivera|Marshall|Hernandez|2010|p=256}} Recordings often reflect lyrics and dance routines suggesting [[doggy style]] sex, exemplifying machismo behavior and [[hypermasculinity]].{{sfn|Rivera|Marshall|Hernandez|2010|pp=2, 253, 256}} Most reggaeton songs "[circumscribe women] to dancing and fulfilling male sexual desire", which "eliminates almost all possibility of action and translates their presence into a prize or trophy that men exhibit, dominate, and manipulate."{{sfn|Rivera|Marshall|Hernandez|2010|p=256}} In Ivy Queen's song, "[[Chika Ideal]]", the singer introduces her female friend to "the dance floor to satisfy her man's fantasies and answer (with her body) each time he wants to call her."{{sfn|Rivera|Marshall|Hernandez|2010|p=256}} In reggaeton music videos, women often act out or "beg for sexual action" from male musicians.{{sfn|Rivera|Marshall|Hernandez|2010|p=269}} In [[Residente]]'s music video for "[[Chulin Culin Chunfly]]", women wore costumes and played police officers, bartenders, and servers.{{sfn|Rivera|Marshall|Hernandez|2010|p=270}} Before reggaeton became popular, Cuban singer [[Pedro Calvo]] invited preteens and middle-aged women onstage and began to "[go] [[Oral sex|down on them]]".{{sfn|Rivera|Marshall|Hernandez|2010|p=289}} Sexuality among young women in Cuba has been viewed as "normative learning behavior" descended from the Afro-Cuban [[Palo religion]], where men and women dance closely before "the man goes behind the women in a picaresque way" and emulates a "gesture of appreciation".{{sfn|Rivera|Marshall|Hernandez|2010|p=289}} Cover images of reggaeton records often feature women who are "voluptuous, provocative, and scantily clad."{{sfn|Rivera|Marshall|Hernandez|2010|p=263}}

=== Latin pop ===
[[File:ThaliaSodi.jpg|thumb|alt=A smiling Thalía making a TV commercial|[[Thalía]] became popular during the 1990s after her Latin-music debut.]]
Selena's music [[List of people influenced by Selena|influenced]] Jennifer Lopez,{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=688}}{{sfn|Mendoza|2004|p=289}} who played the singer in her 1997 [[Selena (film)|biographical film]] and debuted in the Latin music market with salsa singer Marc Anthony on the 1999 single "[[No Me Ames]]".{{sfn|Lannert|2000 (b)|p=107}} Lopez remained in the [[American pop]] market through the early 2000s and returned to Latin music with her Spanish-language debut, ''[[Como Ama Una Mujer]]'', in 2006.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=668}} The album was a commercial success, debuting in the top ten of the ''Billboard'' 200 and joining the handful of Hispanic artists with an album in the chart's top ten.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=668}} Mexican actress and singer [[Thalía]] debuted on the Latin music scene during the early 1990s.{{sfn|Candelaria|2004|p=835}} In mid-decade the singer became commercially successful, with her album ''[[En Éxtasis]]'' (1995) certified platinum.{{sfn|Candelaria|2004|p=835}} She contributed to three tracks for the 1997 soundtrack of [[Fox Animation Studios]]' ''[[Anastasia (1997 film)|Anastasia]]''.{{sfn|Candelaria|2004|p=835}} Thalía's lyrics explore "women or men in a narcissistic, [[neoliberal]], first-world context but do not make sense in the general context of Latin American ordinary life" attributed to other female performers, such as the Mexican singer [[Paulina Rubio]] and the Spanish singer [[Belinda Lima|Belinda]].{{sfn|Bixler|Seda|2009|p=173}} Thalía and Rubio have been called "young, blonde, and thin", wearing "fashionable" clothing, whose "dull" lyrics assume the role of a "seductive, sexy, young woman who wants a macho-man at heart."{{sfn|Bixler|Seda|2009|p=173}} According to musicologists Jacqueline Eyring Bixler and Laurietz Seda, Thalía and Rubio's music does not address "mature and/or working-class women".{{sfn|Bixler|Seda|2009|p=173}}

[[File:Shakira - Glastonbury Festival 2010.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Shakira onstage, singing and playing guitar|[[Shakira]] achieved mainstream success after the 2001 release of "[[Whenever, Wherever|Suerte]]".]]
[[Shakira]]'s major-label debut, ''[[Pies Descalzos]]'' (1995), was the singer's "breakthrough album" in the Latin-music market and yielded the hit single "[[Estoy Aquí]]".{{sfn|Fawcett|2011|p=220}}{{sfn|D'Amore|López|2012}} She had a Latin [[pop rock]] sound, influenced by [[Middle Eastern music|Middle Eastern]] and [[Latin American music]].{{sfn|Doeden|2017|p=50}} Shakira continued her career with the [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Rock, Urban or Alternative Album|Grammy Award for Best Latin Rock Album]]-nominated ''[[Dónde Están los Ladrones?]]'' (1998),{{sfn|Anon.|1999}} and joined Gloria Estefan and her husband, [[Emilio Estefan|Emilio]], to produce her first English-language album; it yielded "[[Whenever, Wherever|Suerte]]", which brought her mainstream success.{{sfn|Martínez|2003|p=213}} Formed in 2006 in Argentina, the Kumbia Queers have recorded [[cumbia]] and Latin pop tracks with "ironic and witty articulations of {{sic|[[lesbianism]]}} desire".{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=268}}

In Spain, [[Lola Flores]] is hailed as the queen of [[flamenco music]] and Rocío Jurado is considered "one of the purest voices of all time" in the country.{{sfn|Simonis|2007|p=31}} Music executive Lynn Santiago, who represented [[Yolandita Monge]], Lissette Melendez, and [[Vikki Carr]] during the 1980s, said in a ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' interview that she wanted "to represent only a few artists in order to give them individual attention." Latin pop musicians from Puerto Rico, such as [[Lucecita Benítez]] and Monge, had male promoters who wanted to "bring local performers" by "offering a big fiesta for the people [of Puerto Rico]."{{sfn|Santiago|1986|p=32}} Other Latin pop musicians popular in Puerto Rico during the 1980s include Conchita Alonso, Maggy, Lunna "Cheo" Feliciano, Sophy Hernandez, and the Argentine duo [[Pimpinela]].{{sfn|Santiago|1986|pp=12, 44}} In mainstream pop, female musicians [[Mariah Carey]],{{sfn|Anon.|1999|p=30}} [[Debelah Morgan]],{{sfn|Riviezzi|2013}} [[Jessica Simpson]], [[Celine Dion]], [[Carole King]], [[Tina Arena]], [[Gloria Gaynor]], [[Alexia (Italian singer)|Alexia]], [[Jennifer Rush]], [[Lara Fabian]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Laura Pausini]],{{sfn|Anon.|n.d. (a)}} [[Beyoncé]], [[Selena Gomez]],{{sfn|Nunez|2014}} [[Demi Lovato]], [[Azealia Banks]], [[Ariana Grande]], and [[Toni Braxton]]{{sfn|Huerta|2015}} often record Spanish-language versions of their songs.

After winning the inaugural Festival of Latin Song in Puerto Rico in 1969, Lucecita Benítez "single-handedly put Puerto Rico on the map."{{sfn|Fiol-Matta|2017|p=2}} Her winning song, "[[Génesis (Lucecita Benítez song)|Génesis]]", expressed "extreme male melancholy"; author Licia Fiol-Matta called Benitez a "masculine female" whose delivery "unexpectedly delivered this affect home."{{sfn|Fiol-Matta|2017|p=2}} Throughout her career, Benítez performed and recorded compositions atypical of Puerto Rican music; nonconforming to gender roles, they did not address heterosexual desire.{{sfn|Fiol-Matta|2017|p=2}} She survived several silencing attempts by those who disliked her music.{{sfn|Fiol-Matta|2017|p=2}} Women remain a minority in Puerto Rican music, although singers [[Myrta Silva]], [[Ruth Fernandez]], Ernestina Reyes, and La Calandria have achieved moderate success.{{sfn|Fiol-Matta|2017}}

=== Rock en Español===
{{see also|Women in rock}}
[[File:Alejandra Guzmán at Denver Coliseum 2.jpg|alt=Alejandra Guzmán crouching onstage|thumb|[[Alejandra Guzmán]] has been called the "bad girl" of Latin pop and the queen of Latin American rock music.]]
The 1989 single "Virginidad Sacudida" by Mexican [[hardcore punk]] band Secta Suicida Siglo explores [[sexual repression]] among women, challenged [[heterosexism]] in Latin music, and opposed refraining from [[premarital sex]] for fear of being called a prostitute.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=268}} Colombian singer [[Andrea Echeverri]]'s music "underlines the hybrid nature of Latin American culture"; called the most-important female [[rock en español]] interpreter, she "incorporates [her music with] the past rather than refusing it or mocking it."{{sfn|Tompkins|Foster|2001|p=86}} Echeverri is the lead singer of [[Aterciopelados]], the only female-led [[rock en español]] band.{{sfn|Tompkins|Foster|2001|p=86}} She pursues a feminist agenda with her music, which has made her popular in the "most revolutionary and controversial musical genres in Latin America."{{sfn|Tompkins|Foster|2001|p=86}} The singer grew up encouraged by her mother to sing boleros, ballads, and rancheras.{{sfn|Tompkins|Foster|2001|p=87}} She decided to continue her education in the arts, returning to music during the 1980s. Echeverri joined Delia y Los Aminoácidos in the 1990s; influenced by [[punk music|punk]] and hardcore music, the band's name was later changed to the Aterciopelados.{{sfn|Tompkins|Foster|2001|p=87}} Because of Echeverri's interest the band's repertoire focused on women's issues, with lyrics about women's relationships with men, and performed songs exploring domestic abuse, denouncing [[misogyny]] and "overdramatized passionate love", and examining Latin America's ideology and history of traditional love.{{sfn|Tompkins|Foster|2001|p=87}} As her popularity grew, Echeverri became a feminist icon and released an [[underground music|underground recording]]: ''[[Con el Corazón en la Mano (Aterciopelados album)|Con el Corazón en la Mano]]'' (1993).{{sfn|Tompkins|Foster|2001|p=87}} The album, intended as a [[demo (music)|demo]], reached the top ten in Colombia and piqued the interest of [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG Music Group]] and [[MTV]].{{sfn|Tompkins|Foster|2001|p=87}} The band followed with ''[[El Dorado (Aterciopelados album)|El Dorado]]'' (1995) and went to [[London]] to produce ''[[La Pipa de la Paz]]'' (1996), which was certified gold in Colombia and received Aterciopelados' first nomination for the [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Rock, Urban or Alternative Album|Grammy Award for Best Latin Alternative Music Album]].{{sfn|Tompkins|Foster|2001|p=87}}

[[File:Aterciopelados - Bumbershoot 2010 - 47.jpg|left|thumb|alt=Andrea Echeverri playing guitar onstage, punching the air with her fist|[[Andrea Echeverri]]'s repertoire has focused on women's issues.]]
Although some female Latin singers have explored a range of feminist topics, including [[sexism]], [[domestic abuse]], and "reclaiming women's sexuality through their music", others (such as [[Julieta Venegas]]) have refrained from labeling themselves as feminists.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=268}} Venegas said in a 2004 interview that her music has a "feminine point of view" and does not delve into feminism.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=268}} Chilean [[Folklore|folklorist]] [[Violeta Parra]] recorded songs about failed heterosexual relationships, emphasizing men's incapability to commit to a woman.{{sfn|Fiol-Matta|2017}} Called the "bad girl" of Latin pop and the queen of Latin American rock music, [[Alejandra Guzmán]] has attained "tabloid notoriety for her flesh-baring displays on stage and for a series of controversial moves and wrong turns in her personal life"{{sfn|Manheim|n.d.}} but has been credited with breaking barriers in Latin music for women.{{sfn|Manheim|n.d.}} Her parents, [[Enrique Guzmán]] and [[Silvia Pinal]], often recorded and performed music together and were considered the Mexican [[Sonny and Cher]].{{sfn|Manheim|n.d.}}

=== {{anchor|Portuguese music genres}}Portuguese music ===
[[Image:Arte Amalia.jpg|alt=Mural of a seated Amália Rodrigues playing a lute-like instrument|thumb|Portuguese singer Amália Rodrigues is considered the best-known fado musician.]]
In [[Music of Portugal|Portuguese music]], [[Amália Rodrigues]] is considered the "best-known and most famous" ''[[fado|fadista]]'' by author Paul Buck;{{sfn|Buck|2002|p=98}} Rodrigues' lyrics were written by "the most celebrated [[poet]]s and writers of the day."{{sfn|Buck|2002|p=98}} The singer was instrumental in popularizing fado, "attract[ing] attention around the world."{{sfn|Buck|2002|p=98}} [[Ana Moura]] has emerged in modern fado with "transcendent singing [which] personifies [fado music]" and lyrics reflecting "lost love, separation, and longing."{{sfn|Anon.|2006|p=65}} Fado, a traditional folk genre popular in [[Lisbon]], was once a male enclave.{{sfn|Colvin|2016|p=97}} Female singers such as [[Mariza]],{{sfn|Colvin|2016|p=147}} [[Mísia]], [[Mafalda Arnauth]], [[Dulce Pontes]], [[Cristina Branco]], Joana Amendoeira, [[Raquel Tavares]], [[Yolanda Soares]] and Kátia Guerreiro have reinvigorated modern fado.{{sfn|Rother|2011}} In Portuguese folk, [[Teresa Salgueiro]]'s "rich and enchanting" vocals have been praised.{{sfn|Lochery|2017}} Other Portuguese female singers (Felipa Pais, Marta Dias, Sofia Varela, [[Anabella]], Bevinda, [[Sara Tavares]], [[Cesaria Evora]], [[Maria João]], [[Marisa Monte]], and [[Lura (singer)|Lura]]) have attained moderate success in the country.{{sfn|Berne|1999|pp=91-99}} [[Cristina Pato]],{{sfn|Berne|1999|pp=91-99}} Xiradela, Leilia, Ialma, and Donicelas "represent the rediscovery of the importance of female singers in [[Music of Galicia, Cantabria and Asturias|Galician]] traditional music."{{sfn|Miguélez-Carballeira|2014|p=112}} Ugia Pedreira, the Galician lead singer of Marful, "mixes traditional Galician song with new jazz arrangements [and] harmonies."{{sfn|Miguélez-Carballeira|2014|p=112}}

[[Daniela Mercury]] is one of the "best-known Brazilian female singers".{{sfn|Afolabi|2016|p=238}} During the 1950s, some female singers in [[Brazil]] were called prostitutes and risked being labeled "promiscuous or masculine ... [or] lesbians".{{sfn|Kottak|2016|p=231}} According to authors Oliver Marshall, Dilwyn Jenkins and David Cleary, the country has "a strong tradition of producing excellent female singers".{{sfn|Marshall|Jenkins|Cleary|2009}} They list [[Elis Regina]], [[Gal Costa]], [[Marisa Monte]], Silvia Torres, Belô Velloso, and [[Fernanda Porto]] as examples of the sizable roster of women in Brazilian music.{{sfn|Marshall|Jenkins|Cleary|2009}}

== {{anchor|Commercial visibility and decline of women in Latin music}}Visibility ==
[[File:The opening ceremony of the FIFA World Cup 2014 10 (cropped) 2.jpg|thumb|alt=Jennifer Lopez singing onstage|[[Jennifer Lopez]] and others have been credited with increasing the visibility of women in Latin music.]]
Although women have been credited with reshaping Latin music and public perceptions of sexuality, gender, and feminism,{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=269}} the Latin music industry remains male-dominated.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=267}} American musicologist Ilan Stavans credits Selena, Jenni Rivera, Jennifer Lopez, Ivy Queen, Julieta Venegas, and [[Ely Guerra]] for the visibility of women in Latin music.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=267}} [[NPR]] named [[Maluca]], [[Bomba Estereo]], La Lupe, [[Gloria Trevi]], [[Chavela Vargas]], [[Tita Merello]], as "''las mostras'', fierce women of Latin music."{{sfn|Garsd|2016}} ''Billboard'' magazine named Selena as a "role model to Latinas everywhere",{{sfn|Anon.|2016}} and ''[[Latina (magazine)|Latina]]'' magazine named Gloria Estefan as "a role model for women across the globe."{{sfn|Palomares|2013}} According to ''Latina'', singers [[Rita Moreno]], Selena, Gloria Estefan, Celia Cruz, Shakira, and Jennifer Lopez "changed the world" with their work, achieved "more and [gave] more."{{sfn|Palomares|2013}} With Selena, Jenni Rivera has been credited with the visibility of women in regional Mexican music with the "very large population of [[Mexican American]] women in the United States [with whom they] could identify".{{sfn|Cobo|2013|p=1993}} In Tejano music, Selena's popularity has helped "open the doors" to other female singers.{{sfn|San Miguel|2002|p=118}} Because of the singer's influence, women in Tejano music emerged "as a significant [demographic]" in the genre during the 1990s and major record labels began increasing their female representation.{{sfn|San Miguel|2002|p=118}} After Selena, women were "a significant part of [the Tejano and regional Mexican music] industry."{{sfn|San Miguel|2002|p=118}} Her ''Dreaming of You'' (1995) album topped the ''Billboard'' 200 chart, the first Hispanic artist and the first woman to do so.{{sfn|Dickerson|2010}} At the turn of the 21st century, Thalía, Paulina Rubio, Jennifer Lopez, Shakira, and [[Pilar Montenegro]] were the most popular female Latin pop singers.{{sfn|Cobo|2013|p=1}} Graciela Beltran, Jennifer Pena, [[Ana Gabriel]], and [[Paquita la del Barrio]] were the most popular female singers in their respective regional-Mexican genres,{{sfn|Cobo|2013|p=1}} but female singers remain "rare" in regional Mexican music.{{sfn|Cobo|2013|p=1}} ''[[People en Espanol]]'' named singers [[Lucero (entertainer)|Lucero]], [[Chiquis Rivera]], and Jennifer Lopez in its 2017 list of the top 25 most-powerful Latina women.{{sfn|Diaz|2017}} ''Billboard'' released a list of the top 100 music executives, which included Maria Fernandez (senior vice president operations and CFO of Latin Iberia-[[Sony Music Entertainment]]) and Rocio Guerrero (global head of Latin content programming for [[Spotify]]).{{sfn|Anon.|2016 (b)}}

Although women in mariachi music are perceived to be widely accepted, contemporary female singers in the genre have found it an "unwelcoming environment for females."{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=467}} According to the [[Duranguense]] group Los Horóscopos de Durango, in 21st-century regional Mexican music it is "hard for women to actually be respected, to be taken into consideration, to be given the time to show [their] talent."{{sfn|Guerra|2015}} The group has found the genre a "struggle" because of male dominance.{{sfn|Guerra|2015}} In 2017, [[Univision]] broadcast the [[reality television]] competition show ''La Reina de la Canción'' (''Queen of Song''), in which participants with "the best voices, compelling stories, and a desire to become a superstar" compete to become the next star of regional Mexican music.{{sfn|Villafañe|2017}} ''Billboard'' executive director of Latin content and programming [[Leila Cobo]] wrote that the public perception of regional Mexican music is a group of men dressed as cowboys.{{sfn|Cobo|2007|p=24}} In the 2004 and 2005 year-end charts, only one female in the genre reached the top twenty; in 2006, there were three.{{sfn|Cobo|2007|p=24}} That year, three singles by women topped the Hot Latin Songs chart: Shakira's collaborative single with [[Wyclef Jean]], "[[Hips Don't Lie]]"; Paulina Rubio's "[[Ni Una Sola Palabra]]", and [[Anaïs (singer)|Anais]]' "[[Lo Que Son Las Cosas]]".{{sfn|Cobo|2009|p=10}} In 2008, there were no number-one singles by a woman on the Latin music charts.{{sfn|Cobo|2009|p=10}} Early in 2009 Jennifer Lopez ended the drought with "[[Qué Hiciste]]" (number one for a week), followed by Gloria Estefan's "[[No Llores]]" and [[Fanny Lu]]'s "[[Y Si Te Digo]]".{{sfn|Cobo|2009|p=10}} In August 2009 three women (Shakira, Paulina Rubio, and [[Nelly Furtado]]) made the top ten of the Hot Latin Songs chart, a "rare occurrence".{{sfn|Cobo|2009|p=10}} According to industry observers, women on the charts are "cyclical, as every couple of years a burst of estrogen appears on the typically testosterone-dominated Latin charts."{{sfn|Cobo|2009|p=10}}

[[File:Jenni Rivera in Concert.jpg|thumb|alt=Jenni Rivera taking a break during a performance|[[Jenni Rivera]]'s recordings have sparked debate in the [[Latino]] community on women's roles.{{sfn|Stavans|2009|p=671}}]]
Women finalists at the 2016 [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]] were outnumbered by men, which was described by the magazine as a "continuing [challenge] facing female artists in Latin music."{{sfn|Anon.|2016}} For 2017 [[International Women's Day]] and [[Women's History Month]], the [[music streaming]] service Spotify curated a playlist of women in Latin music.{{sfn|Flores|2017}} The playlist included music from Selena, Celia Cruz, and [[Natalia Lafourcade]].{{sfn|Flores|2017}} An April 2016 ''Billboard'' report noted the absence of women from the magazine's [[music chart]]s.{{sfn|Cobo|2016}} The report found that the last female soloist topped the US [[Hot Latin Songs]] chart four years earlier: Shakira, with [[Maná]] (a male rock en español group), singing "[[Mi Verdad (song)|Mi Verdad]]".{{sfn|Cobo|2016}} In 2012 seven women had number-ones on the Top Latin Albums chart, compared with 33 men.{{sfn|Cobo|2016}} ''Billboard'' executive Leila Cobo found that three of the seven women were veterans (Gloria Trevi, Thalía, and [[Ednita Nazario]]), and another three were deceased (Selena, Jenni Rivera, and [[Natalie Cole]].{{sfn|Cobo|2016}} [[Leslie Grace]] was the youngest female singer to reach number one on the [[Latin Airplay]] chart when she was 17 years old,{{sfn|Cobo|2016}} and Alexandra Lioutikoff was the first woman executive vice-president at [[Universal Music Publishing Group]]'s Latin division.{{sfn|Cobo|2016}} Asked why the visibility of women in Latin music has declined, [[Chiquis Rivera]] suggested that radio programmers are to blame for their "''machista'' culture."{{sfn|Cobo|2016}} According to Lioutikoff, women (unlike their male counterparts) "rarely collaborate".{{sfn|Cobo|2016}} In its report, ''Billboard'' compiled a list of the top five women with the most number-ones on the Hot Latin Songs; Gloria Estefan led the list with 15, Shakira had 10, Selena seven, Ana Gabriel six, and Paulina Rubio five.{{sfn|Cobo|2016}} The magazine found women "underrepresented on the Latin-music-focused ''Billboard'' charts", with Rubio the last female number-one with "Me Gustas Todo" on February 11, 2012.{{sfn|Cobo|2016}} A discrepancy existed between the Top Latin Albums and the ''Billboard'' 200 charts; seven women topped the Latin Albums chart, compared to 21 on the ''Billboard'' 200.{{sfn|Cobo|2016}}

Women remain a minority in Puerto Rican music.{{sfn|Fiol-Matta|2017}} According to Licia Fiol-Matta, the [[music industry]] has a "prejudiced practice of limiting the number of women recording artists" and women singers "did not sell records since women did not buy records."{{sfn|Fiol-Matta|2017}} In July 2017, Alejandra Guzmán and Gloria Trevi were the first female collaboration in the 24-year history of the Top Latin Albums chart to debut atop the chart.{{sfn|Zellner|2017}} In 2016, Mexican pop singer [[Sofia Reyes]] was the first female lead singer with a number-one single in five years.{{sfn|Benjamin|2017}} Her collaboration with [[Prince Royce]] on "[[Solo Yo]]" was the first number-one single on the [[Latin Pop Songs]] chart by a woman since Jennifer Lopez' "[[On the Floor|Ven A Bailar]]" (2011) with [[Pitbull (entertainer)|Pitbull]].{{sfn|Benjamin|2017}} Eight women have topped the Latin Pop Songs chart as featured acts, duos or groups with female leads: "Solo Yo" (Sofia Reyes with Prince Royce, April 23, 2016); "Mi Verdad" ([[Maná]], featuring Shakira, April 4, 2015); "[[Corre!]]" ([[Jesse & Joy]], March 31, 2012); "[[Dutty Love]]" ([[Don Omar]] with [[Natti Natasha]], March 24, 2012), "[[Fuiste Tu]]" ([[Ricardo Arjona]] with [[Gaby Moreno]], March 10, 2012); "[[Give Me Everything]]" (Pitbull with [[Ne-Yo]], [[Afrojack]] and [[Nayer]], July 23, 2011), and "Ven A Bailar" (Jennifer Lopez with Pitbull, June 18, 2011).{{sfn|Mendizabal|2016}} Amaya Mendizabal of ''Billboard'' called the decline of women on the Latin music charts "an ongoing trend."{{sfn|Mendizabal|2016}} In 2015, 22 weeks passed without a female-led single on the 50-position Hot Latin Songs chart.{{sfn|Mendizabal|2016}} According to Mendizabal, the absence of women on the Latin music charts is "partly attributed to the steady popularity of reggaeton and regional Mexican music, which is often led by male acts."{{sfn|Mendizabal|2016}} Mendizabal wrote that "traditional pop songs" rarely top the Hot Latin Songs chart; four pop songs did so in the previous three years, most by men.{{sfn|Mendizabal|2016}} Sofia Reyes has expressed concern about the lack of women performers at Latin-music awards shows, telling Jeff Benjamin of [[Fuse TV]] that 90 percent of awards-show performers are men.{{sfn|Benjamin|2017}}

In July 2017, Spanish writer Daniela Bose noted the absence of women in Spanish music charts in comparison with those of [[Music of France|France]] and [[Music of Italy|Italy]]; culturally similar to Spain, women were more successful in the latter countries.{{sfn|Bose|2017}} Bose analyzed the [[Spanish Albums Chart|Spanish Albums]] and [[Spanish Singles Chart|Singles Charts]], finding that the only Spanish singers who placed in the top 50 were [[Malú]], [[Vanesa Martin]], Sweet California, [[India Martinez]], and the [[Spanish folk music]] singers [[Mónica Naranjo]] and [[Isabel Pantoja]].{{sfn|Bose|2017}} When Bose expanded her search to the next 50 positions, she found only non-Spanish singers.{{sfn|Bose|2017}} She concluded that listeners had replaced Spanish and [[Latin pop]] music with reggaeton and [[Trap music (hip hop)|trap music]], genres performed by men with lyrics belittling women "as meat".{{sfn|Bose|2017}} Bose found a [[subtext]] in the songs encouraging female [[infidelity]] for sexual reasons, alluding to a non-committed relationship.{{sfn|Bose|2017}} According to Bose, music "is not one of those 'secure' professions [for those who] seek stability"; she found women absent from prominent positions held by men, such as heading a record label, producing concerts, and [[audio engineer]]ing; in these fields, with higher pay and power, women lack "decision-making process[es] that set the path for [the Latin music] industry."{{sfn|Bose|2017}} She ended her report by urging the music industry to avoid gender imbalances in their markets: "What dazzles is the beauty of the final work, regardless of who creates it."{{sfn|Bose|2017}}

